body:
Arthur Mattuck in his Introduction to Analysis book, pg. 220 says, in order
to prove L'Hospital's Rule for $\infty/\infty$ case, Let $L=\lim_{x \to \infty} \frac{f'(x)}{g'(x)}$ and choose $a$ so that $\frac{f'(x)}{g'(x)} \stackrel{\approx}{\epsilon} L$  for $x>a$. And prove two approximations below (valid for $x\gg 1$) $$ \frac{f(x)}{g(x)} \stackrel{\approx}{\epsilon}
\frac{f(x)-f(a)}{g(x)-g(a)} \stackrel{\approx}{\epsilon}
L
$$ His hint is, for the first approximation, that we write $$ f(x) - f(a) = f(x) [ 1 - f(a)/f(x)] $$ and use limit theorem, for the second, use the Cauchy Mean-value Theorem. Anyone know how to pursue this proof? Thanks,
